<TEXT>
the communist leaders of isolated 
albania europes last bastion of stalinism have staunchly denied 
any intention of relinquishing their independence and following the 
trend toward democracy in eastern europe 
but communist leader ramiz alia may come under increasing 
pressure to change both from abroad and inside the country where 
cautious reforms increasingly conflict with adherence to the rigid 
communism of albanias founding father enver hoxha 
there were unconfirmed reports of unrest at tirana universitys 
student dorms last summer yugoslav media in reports denied by 
albanian officials have spoken of antigovernment protests in the 
cities of shkodra and korca last fall 
king leka i the pretender to albanias throne who has lived in 
south africa for the past 10 years said in an interview published 
friday that leaflets urging albanians to overthrow their hardline 
government will be dropped by balloon into the closed balkan nation 
bordering the adriatic 
albanian emigre groups in europe meanwhile are said by the 
yugoslav news agency tanjug to have petitioned west european 
parliaments to help the albanians win freedom 
outwardly alia has shown no sign of yielding to such pressure 
in a new years message to his people he denounced what he called 
a foreign campaign of slanders to get albania to follow the 
democratic trends in eastern europe 
the very reference to eastern europe and the specific reference 
to campaigns abroad may indicate that alia faces questions about 
reform at home 
on dec 12 alia justified the refusal to follow eastern europe 
by stressing that albania which severed ties with moscow in 1961 
and china in 1978 is not like other communist countries 
processes like those in eastern europe will not occur in 
albania he said albania and eastern europe have developed 
along completely different ideological political economic and 
social roads he added 
albania is the last east european country to revere josef 
stalin whose giant statue stands in the capital tirana 
even more important is hoxha he died in 1985 but his name 
remains sacred for albanias leaders who last year opened a 
costly grandiose museum in tirana that is intended to enshrine his 
every deed and word in the national memory 
vistors to tirana report that groups of schoolchildren are 
guided repeatedly through the museum as part of their rigid 
education as loyal citizens of albania 
yet there are signs that young people particularly are 
increasingly influenced by the italian yugoslav and greek 
television broadcasts that amuse them instead of albanian tv which 
broadcasts only in the evening 
the attitude of the young whose protests sparked the 
revolutions that toppled orthodox communists in east germany 
czechoslovakia and romania is particularly important in albania 
which has one of the highest birthrates in europe 
perhaps because of youths importance louis zanga an albanian 
specialist at the usfinanced radio free europe radio station 
noted in august and september an unusual discussion of taboo topics 
such as youths love of rock music and fashions they cant find in 
albanian stores 
according to zanga youth union leader mehmet elezi criticized 
conservative bureaucrats for their handling of a poll of young 
people who on guarantee of anonymity unexpectedly spoke of their 
love for rock music 
tomorrow in a similar situation young people will not 
respond for fear of getting into trouble elezi reportedly said 
and how will we then be able to figure out their thoughts 
media in neighboring yugoslavia which accuses albania of 
fomenting unrest in its southern province of kosovo have detected 
some other signs of change 
the belgrade daily politika noted for example that a book 
recently published by a former albanian interior minister neshat 
tozai described apparently for the first time harassment by the 
dreaded sigurimi or security police 
romanias 23 million citizens eventually rose up against nicolae 
ceausescus equally feared security network but there are only 32 
million albanians to control and they have been virtually cut off 
from the world since 1944 far longer than romanians 
but over the past two years cultural exhibitions have brought 
albanians glimpses of west german and french arts popular italian 
singers toured last fall 
ambiguities abound in politics and economics alia in an 
apparent effort to assure albanians they live in a democracy 
constantly exhorts officials to be closer to the people yet 
asserts that only communists can rule 
in the staterun economy official plans are constantly reported 
to be more than fulfilled yet every leaders speech talks of 
deformations and problems in industry and agriculture 
a severe drought last year caused rationing of energy much of 
which comes from hydropower and alias bleak new years message 
was more of the same economic austerity measures are demanded 
everywhere he said 
</TEXT>
