<TEXT>
bridget mergens and a group of friends wanted 
to start a high school club something like the chess club only 
they would discuss the bible 
five years later bridget mergens mayhew now married and the 
mother of a 13monthold girl is making her first trip to 
washington to listen to arguments before the us supreme court in 
a case that could provide an important ruling on churchstate 
relations 
the court will hear an appeal tuesday by omaha westside high 
school officials who say allowing a bible study group to meet at 
the school after class would violate the constitutionally required 
separation of church and state 
mrs mergens mayhew came from a roman catholic family joined an 
interdenominational church group in high school and now is a member 
of the assembly of god she wasnt expecting trouble when she asked 
to start the bible group 
we wanted to be like the chess club but talk about biblical 
things she said friday it scared the school so much 
by accepting the case the justices agreed to review a 1984 
federal law requiring that student religious groups receive the 
same access as other extracurricular clubs to public high school 
facilities 
westside school officials said a school policy requiring clubs 
to be curriculumrelated and have a school sponsor meant their 
decision to keep out the bible club was not in violation of the 
federal equal access act 
principal james findley said he initially thought no 
problem when miss mergens then a senior said others at the 
1500student school wanted to get together to read the bible and 
pray the problem arose when the students wanted the group to be 
recognized as a club meeting after school hours he said 
school officials saw that as a violation of the separation of 
church and state and had other concerns findley said 
our interpretation was once we let that group meet we would 
have to let any group meet he said if a satanist club wanted 
to meet we think wed have to allow that to happen those were our 
concerns 
school officials said students are free to discuss religious 
subjects but they cant expect the school to endorse them and 
permit equal access to all school resources 
mrs mergens mayhew who lives in nearby bellevue said she 
feels the school discriminated against the students who wanted the 
bible group 
for me its a religious issue she said but its 
important for more than the religious community 
as the case went through the federal courts she found herself 
reading about the constitution and the nations founders 
they were religious men they were godly men they didnt want 
one colony to push one religion on them they wanted to pursue it 
on their own thats why they wrote the constitution the way they 
did she said our forefathers were sharp guys 
the supreme court ruled in 1981 that state universities cannot 
ban student groups from using campus facilities for religious 
worship and study but the justices have not decided if the rule 
should apply to high schools 
in the mergens case a federal court ruled in favor of the 
school district but the 8th us circuit court of appeals 
overturned the decision 
the appeals court rejected the contention that high school 
students are more impressionable than college students and should 
be protected from student religious groups that may appear to be 
sanctioned by school authorities 
robert skolrood executive director of the national legal 
foundation which is helping mrs mergens mayhew said he would be 
terribly disappointed if the high court didnt uphold the 
appellate decision 
the students should be allowed to meet because it was their 
decision not the school establishing a religion he said that 
means the case could have implications for the question of school 
prayer he said 
students have every right to do it if its not the school 
determining it he said 
dick shugrue a creighton university law professor said the 
courts decision may be made on much narrower grounds 
those backing the mergens side believe if the case succeeds it 
will be a stake in the heart of the high courts 1963 ban on 
school prayer shugrue said 
the hope of the mergens supporters is that the court would 
say we made a tragic mistake by golly lets put god back in 
the public schools shugrue said 
</TEXT>
