oklahoma may be the state song but 
that doesnt mean its the states song 
oklahoma tourism officials discovered that recently when they 
used the song in television ads 
the tourism department paid more than 17000 to play parts of 
the song in commercials to attract tourists from neighboring states 
when tourism director glenn sullivan learned the state had paid 
to use its own state song in a nonprofit endeavor he asked his 
staff to see if a refund was possible 
a staffer uncovered a letter from lyricist oscar hammerstein ii 
that had been entered into the 1953 legislative journal after a 
similar dispute 
tell your readers and all the people of oklahoma that not only 
may they play and sing it anywhere and everywhere to their hearts 
content but that we want them and urge them to do so 
hammersteins letter said 
his only restrictions were that the song not be used in a play 
or against any dramatic background 
but officials from albertco which now owns rights to the 
rodgers and hammerstein musical oklahoma said friday they 
would not grant a refund 
albertco said the published copy of hammersteins letter was not 
signed and is not legally binding 
tourism spokesman steve paris said the company appears to have a 
strong case he said the department still may ask the attorney 
general for an opinion 
tourism advertising manager dennis donaldson said it hardly 
seems fair that the state should have to continue paying to use the 
song or change the ads 
after all we let them use our state to do a play 
</TEXT>
