at least 6000 people were killed in 
sri lanka in 1989 in political violence associated with an uprising 
by ultranationalist sinhalese and a rebellion by tamil 
separatists military officials say 
the officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said at 
least 500 people were killed each month as the sinhalese militant 
movement gained momentum and tamil rebels turned their guns against 
other members of their ethnic minority 
the officials were speaking in response to a newspaper report 
published sunday that said at least 12000 people were killed 
during the year the sunday times said an average of 1000 people 
died each month quoting unidentified military sources 
the tamil separatist revolt which began in 1983 has claimed at 
least 11000 lives at first the sri lankan army tried to quell 
the secessionist campaign then indian peacekeeping troops made an 
attempt 
the fighting now appears to have shifted to a battle for control 
of tamildominated regions of the country between the rebels and 
moderates who accept regional autonomy in exchange for giving up 
the seccessionist campaign 
the indian soldiers are scheduled to leave sri lanka by march 
31 ending a military deployment that began in july 1987 after 
abortive peace overtures to the rebels by the colombo government 
the overtures coupled with the indian military presence 
spawned a backlash by ultranationalist sinhalese militants that 
has escalated into an uprising against the government 
the sinhalese movement launched in 1987 has claimed at least 
6000 lives the killings include hitandrun attacks on government 
supporters by the militants and revenge killings of suspected 
militants by progovernment vigilante groups 
sinhalese comprise 75 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
while tamils account for 18 percent 
tamils launched their separatist agitation amid complaints that 
the sinhalese majority which controls the government and military 
discriminates against them in jobs and education 
