<TEXT>
as a boy growing up on a western 
minnesota dairy farm calvin sperling would comb the douglas county 
countryside collecting bits of plants and trees 
today he travels the globe for the us government searching 
for hundreds of rare and threatened plants that scientists say 
could help feed the planet and save american farmers billions of 
dollars 
as a plant explorer and botanist for the agriculture department 
sperling leads the governments efforts to find seeds of endangered 
species of plants that scientists may someday use to produce better 
varieties of food crops 
sperling hunted for wild lentils and chickpeas in turkey last 
spring he has explored forests in the interior of the soviet union 
for wild apples gone to israel to collect wild wheat and searched 
south american jungles for potato relatives 
ive always had an interest in what was over the next hill 
you might say sperling said in a recent interview at his office 
at usdas agricultural research service 
the future of commercial agriculture could depend on what 
sperling finds 
while whole species of plants are threatened with extinction 
scientists need seeds or germplasm from existing sometimes wild 
varieties of plants to breed the hardier higheryielding crops 
farmers need 
sperlings expeditions provide the raw material for 
biotechnology says donald falk director of harvard universitys 
center for plant conservation 
biotechnology is the future of global agriculture global 
agriculture is the future of being able to feed 10 billion 
people falk said 
what sperling does is so critical to the future of agriculture 
fortune magazine jan 1 named him one of the years 25 most 
fascinating business people 
in his starched shirt and silk tie the wellcoiffed 32yearold 
hardly looks like a botanist who spends weeks at a time crawling 
through brush and jungles in some of the worlds most remote 
regions 
but sperling has had an insatiable curiosity about wild plants 
since he was 12 the alexandria minn native moved from his 
obsession with douglas county flora to study botany at north dakota 
state university later earning advanced degrees in biology at 
harvard 
he joined the agriculture department as a research assistant 
three years ago and was given a permanent position last year as the 
only plant explorer in usdas germplasm services laboratory 
its sperlings job to determine the governments priorities for 
locating the seeds that should be added to its already extensive 
collection 
more than 250000 seed samples are kept in cold storage at 
usdas national seed storage laboratory in fort collins colo 
other samples are stored at an additional 40 locations around the 
country 
a lot of what we do is literally banking were saving things 
that we may need tomorrow sperling said we need to preserve 
as much diversity as we can so its available 
seeds arrive at fort collins from a variety of sources in 
addition to sperlings expeditions other scientists farmers seed 
companies foreign countries and gardeners among the billions of 
seeds in the collection are soybeans from china rice from japan 
and corn from brazil 
at proper temperatures seeds can survive 100 years or more 
what seeds usda scientists can obtain through exchanges with 
foreign governments they do what they cant its sperlings 
responsibility to find 
he may go himself as he did with his trip to the soviet union 
last year for wild apple seeds and cuttings that could lead to 
hardier varieties of the fruit or sperling may provide money and 
technical assistance to university researchers 
sperling spends a quarter of the year in the field the rest 
deciding what should be collected next 
his list of priorities runs from wild cranberries and grapes in 
the united states to wild wheat in north africa and alfalfa in 
southwest asia 
cranberries for example are one of the few crops native to 
america but scientists have never fully surveyed the various wild 
varieties for their useful genetic traits sperling said 
the best cranberry relish ive had was made from cranberries 
in minnesota he said 
harvards falk thinks usdas plant exploration is still vastly 
underfunded but he says sperling has succeeded in steering the 
governments efforts to a wider variety of crops 
one thing he has done with the program is branch into a lot of 
new crops falk said traditionally the government would 
make sort of a halfhearted investment now theres a much more 
aggressive program for a broad range of plant materials 
</TEXT>
