<TEXT>
two agriculture department analysts say the 
1992 plan by the european economic community to bring a 
singlemarket approach to the 12nation trading bloc could mean 
benefits to american exporters including farmers 
a growing eec economy with reduced internal barriers should 
reduce business costs stimulate increased efficiency create new 
wealth and encourage the growth of us exports said richard b 
helm and clay m hamilton of the departments foreign agricultural 
service 
the analysts writing in the january issue of agexporter 
magazine added this should mean an expanded market as long as 
the community does not raise new barriers to compensated member 
states that may be hurt by the liberalized market 
helm and hamilton said the 1992 goal to harmonize tax and 
nontariff differences among member countries in the eec will 
include directives to carry out the plans its hoped that us 
agricultural exports will benefit as existing national laws imposed 
without scientific justification are removed 
however depending on how the 1992 directives are drafted and 
implemented us producers may have to adapt their products or be 
restricted from the eec market as a result of the harmonized 
standards the report said 
food and drink comprise the biggest industry in the eec and is 
probably the one that would benefit most from a single market 
the report said a recent study by the blocs commission identified 
more than 200 nontariff barriers in the food sector including 
requirements for labeling packaging and ingredients 
if harmonized food standards are to be put in place these 
measures should be abolished by the end of 1992 the report said 
however trade barriers in this area may be difficult to 
eliminate because of traditional protectionist pressures or a 
desire to maintain selfsufficiency 
the eec for many years has ranked as a major foreign buyer of 
us agricultural products exports to the bloc in the year that 
ended sept 30 were valued at 66 billion second only to asia as 
a regional foreign market for american farmers 
</TEXT>
