bengurion airport israel ap dressed in heavy overcoats and 
fur hats clutching babies and bulky suitcases the new soviet 
immigrants are arriving in the promised land 
most are driven to leave the soviet union because of a poor 
quality of life and limited opportunities antisemitism and a 
desire to taste freedom while the door stays open 
but unlike the first waves of soviet jewish immigrants few of 
the newcomers consider themselves pioneers ready to sacrifice 
everything to build a nation for the jewish people 
many are driven to israel only by the recent us immigration 
restrictions 
i cant call myself a zionist there was nothing of jewish 
tradition in my family said mikhail weinrub 28 who arrived 
recently with his wife rita 31 and two children 
the influx which jewish agency officials say could total 1 
million by the end of the decade could offset a downward trend in 
jewish population growth and have a dramatic impact on society and 
politics 
in 1989 soviet emigration reached a record 71509 of which 
11994 settled in israel and most of the rest in the united states 
israeli officials predict up to 50000 will arrive in the jewish 
state this year 
newcomers are led into bengurions immigration hall with its 
orange and green plastic chairs aging posters of israeli tourist 
sites and handwritten signs proclaiming in russian all jews are 
brothers 
the weinrubs both hydrogeologists from the black sea port of 
odessa said they had long nurtured a dream of leaving the soviet 
union largely because of antisemitism and economic hardship 
but going to israel did not seem remotely possible 
there were no links with israel at all people were afraid 
even to speak of it weinrub said 
weinrub weary from a sleepless night at moscows sheremetyevo 
airport a bus trip through budapest and a night flight to israel 
listed the reasons for emigrating as his blond wife rita paced 
nervously cradling 18monthold nella 
in odessa the family lived in a single room in a communal 
apartment shared by other families the windows looked onto a 
narrow dark passageway between two adjacent houses 
the only way to move out was to prove the room was dark and be 
placed on a waiting list for a new apartment in 10 to 15 years but 
first they needed a certificate of darkness from officials who 
demanded a bribe that amounted to several years salary or about 
460 to 780 
instead of seeking their own place to live they moved to a 
tworoom apartment they shared with weinrubs parents then to an 
apartment with ritas parents and finally lived with weinrubs aunt 
two years ago emigration restrictions were lifted and their 
life took a new turn 
they found a distant relative in israel who was saved by 
weinrubs grandmother from hunger during world war ii she provided 
an invitation which is needed to start emigration procedures 
early in july the weinrubs applied to emigrate they received a 
visa in october their parents who stayed behind helped the 
couple raise the 1500 in rubles they needed to cancel their 
soviet citizenship and make the trip 
in odessa there was also concern in the jewish community about 
antisemitic slogans shouted in the streets from rightwing youths 
and tensions with ukrainians over housing 
some literary magazines like moscow and nash sovremennik are 
simply antisemitic weinrub said there we read speeches from 
a gathering of russian federation writers and they declared they 
were not antisemitic they only hated jews this was very 
unpleasant 
other immigrants also listed antisemitism as a major motive 
behind the exodus 
there was antisemitism of course just now we heard 
that a pogrom was about to take place on the date of some official 
holiday and the jews stayed home for two days do you remember how 
i was hiding you in the house said brocha much 75 from 
khmelnitzkiy near kiev turning to her small grandson 
we got out only after the radio started to deny that there is 
going to be a pogrom she said 
most immigrants interviewed said they did not believe soviet 
leader mikhail s gorbachevs reforms will succeed 
living standards have dropped national tensions increased and 
the economy deteriorated during perestroika weinrub said of 
gorbachevs reform program i dont believe it would be 
successful 
for him the united states was never an option in part because 
he was put off by letters from friends and relatives who had gone 
to america 
i know what america is like what israel is like nobody knows 
and thats interesting he said i was very impressed by the 
fact that israel has managed to achieve such a level in just 40 
years 
the reasons are different for everyone for roman kopelovitch 
an athletic 24yearold engineer from minsk it was the environment 
yes ecology im an optimist by nature and i dont believe 
in jewish pogroms the situation in minsk was quite pleasant and 
stable he said 
but there is radiation he said referring to fallout from 
the april 1986 accident at the chernobyl nuclear reactor some 200 
miles from minsk the food products are poisoned by nitrates and 
hydrates and nobody cares 
kopelovitch waiting in line to see an immigration officer in a 
tiny airport cubicle said he preferred israel because he brought 
along a sick mother and a small child i would not be able to 
support them in the united states 
surveying the immigrantpacked hall where newcomers were 
filling out typed forms children played or slept in the chairs and 
a youth from uzbekistan clutched a cage of homing pigeons he said 
people are just fleeing from the soviet union from everyday 
hardships antisemitism and other troubles a minority is driven 
by ideology 
but there is something else you keep a lion in a cage and 
then you open a door and the lion leaps out maybe it was wellfed 
in the cage and who knows what will happen outside but the lion 
has been inside the cage for too long 
</TEXT>
