<TEXT>
the trial of an ivy league student accused 
of crippling thousands of computer systems nationwide is viewed by 
computer security experts as a chance to garner support for tougher 
antihacker laws 
its a nolose situation because the trial will showcase the 
weaknesses of computer security and current computer security 
law said harold highland professor emeritus of computer science 
for the state university of new york and editor of computers amp 
security a trade journal 
jury selection was to begin today in the first criminal trial 
under the 1986 federal computer fraud and abuse act 
robert t morris jr a 24yearold suspended cornell university 
graduate student is accused of designing and setting loose a 
computer worm that reproduced wildly in november 1988 
the worm immobilized an estimated 6000 computers linked to a 
research network including computers at the national aeronautics 
and space administration facility at moffet field calif and the 
air force logistics command at wright patterson air force base 
ohio 
it was at cornell that authorities said morris gained access to 
the department of defense network that connects thousands of 
computers at military facilities corporate research centers and 
universities 
a cornell commission concluded that morris was guilty of 
reckless disregard for creating the program although the 
university commission found him responsible morris has never 
admitted creating the program or introducing it into the system 
morris of arnold md faces up to five years in prison and a 
250000 fine if convicted 
with arguments expected to begin later this week in us 
district court computer security experts say the trial will focus 
attention on the need for more stringent computer tampering 
legislation 
if the government loses computer security advocates will 
say there is a need for stronger laws if the government wins 
theyll say he did it because the system is weak and we need to 
tighten up the system highland said 
either way it goes the pure attention is going to fuel the 
cry for tougher laws and better security said christopher a 
breceda a top officer with american computer security industries 
inc a nashville tennbased maker of security systems with 
worldwide sales 
eugene spafford an associate professor of computer science at 
purdue university who has written about the case and is expected to 
be a government witness said losses from computer crimes in the 
united states total about 7 billion annually 
ten years ago these kinds of things didnt hurt anybody but 
you have to realize now all the places where computers are used and 
the dangers involved in shutting down a system or damaging data 
he said 
the worm allegedly created by morris did not destroy any data 
and prosecutors have not estimated the monetary damage from the 
worm but spafford estimated the oneday paralysis cost between 5 
million and 15 million in lost time and in later protective work 
</TEXT>
