the leaning tower whose tilt draws hundreds 
of thousands of tourists a year but could also spell its downfall 
has shut its doors for repairs that officials say could take years 
thousands of sightseers climbed the stairs of the 800yearold 
tower sunday before mayor giacomino granchi locked the doors and 
expressed hope the marble wonder can be reopened soon he 
reluctantly signed an order in december authorizing the closure for 
three months 
but public works minister giovanni prandini who led the drive 
to close the tower told a nationwide television audience he 
expected the tower needed to be closed for several years 
it needs an urgent intervention prandini said but conceded 
there is no agreement yet on the best project to stabilize the 
tower which is a national symbol 
the 180foot tower begun by bonnano pisano in 1173 started to 
tilt almost immediately because the ground shifted underneath the 
tower now leans about 13 feet off the perpendicular 
technicians have said the tower shifted less last year than its 
average annual tilt of the last three decades 003 inches 
compared to an average 0045 inches some experts say the tower 
should stand at least a hundred more years 
the tower is an important source of income for pisa attracting 
about 800000 tourists a year paying 280 apiece to climb the 
spiral staircase 
several thousand tourists turned out sunday with an italian 
soldier the last to go up the 293 steps before the closing 
broadcast by governmentrun raitv 
the tower is an important asset which belongs to everybody 
including the international community we must keep this in mind 
said the mayor 
we have decided to close the tower for three months to do what 
has to be done i dont think it will topple soon and should never 
close i ask the minister to take his responsibility 
