<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected the appeal of 
a tennessee high school student pulled from a race for student 
council president after giving a speech officials deemed 
disrespectful 
the court without comment let stand rulings that officials at 
unicoi county high in erwin tenn did not violate dean polings 
freespeech rights 
poling was a junior running for student council president when 
in may 1987 he delivered a school assembly campaign speech critical 
of the schools administration 
if you want to break the iron grip of this school vote for me 
for president poling told the assembly audience 
he also singled out the schools assistant principal in charge 
of discipline for criticism the admninistration plays tricks 
with your mind and they hope you wont notice for example why 
does mr davidson stutter while he is on the intercom he doesnt 
have a speech impediment poling said 
because of the speech school principal ellis murphy 
disqualified poling from the student council presidency race he 
later was elected president of his senior class 
murphy said polings speech had a disruptive effect on the 
school administrations authority and had shown insensitivity and 
bad taste in its remarks about the assistant principal 
polings parents sued school officials and the school board in 
their sons behalf seeking 300000 in damages for an asserted 
violation of his freespeech rights 
a federal judge threw out the suit without a trial and the 6th 
us circuit court of appeals upheld the dismissal by a 21 vote 
last april 18 
for all we know there may in fact have been an overreaction 
by school authorities the appeals court said but a federal 
court is obviously not the ideal body to try to answer such a 
question 
it added dean poling appears to be an intelligent and 
imaginative young man and probably no more anarchistic than many 
of his teachers at his age like most teenagers dean doubtless 
feels embarrassment very keenly but he may not fully have 
appreciated that the assistant principals of this world are 
sentient beings also some of whom may even be capable of 
experiencing embarrassment themselves 
in a dissenting opinion judge gilbert merritt said polings 
remarks amounted to political speech pure and simple and that 
the action taken against him was unconstitutional 
in a landmark 1969 ruling the supreme court said high school 
students do not shed their constitutional rights to freedom of 
speech or expression at the schoolhouse gate and ruled that 
officials wrongly had banned the wearing of antiwar armbands 
but the court in 1986 gave school administrators broad 
disciplinary powers that include suspending students who use vulgar 
language 
and in 1988 the justices gave school officials new authority to 
censor student newspapers and other forms of student expression at 
schoolsponsored events 
in the appeal acted on today poling said the test for whether 
student speech is constitutionally protected is not rudeness or 
impoliteness but disruption and disorder the appeal said 
polings 1987 speech was not disruptive and caused no disorder 
school officials urged that polings appeal be rejected they 
said that his speech unlike the wearing of an antiwar armband 
did not just happen to occur on school grounds but was part of a 
schoolsponsored activity 
the case is poling vs murphy 89678 
</TEXT>
