<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to review a 
dispute over how much welfare aid some needy families are entitled 
to receive 
the court said it will hear a bush administration appeal aimed 
at limiting the payments in a virginia case 
at issue are features of the aid to families with dependent 
children afdc program 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals last march ruled partly in 
favor of welfare officials and partly in favor of afdc recipients 
the appeals court said social security benefits paid to any 
child in a household must be considered in determining eligibility 
for afdc payments to the family that has the effect of reducing 
afdc payments 
virginia families participating in the program said the us 
department of health and human services in restricting afdc 
benefits misinterpreted a 1984 budgetcutting law 
the 4th circuit court also ruled that the first 50 a month 
families receive in social security benefits must be disregarded 
when determining afdc payments 
the bush administration asked the justices to overturn that part 
of the appeals court decision a separate appeal filed in behalf of 
the virginia families involved in the case was not acted on today 
justice department lawyers said the 50disregard provision 
enacted by congress in 1974 applies only to child support payments 
made by an absent parent and not to social security benefits paid 
to a child of a deceased or disabled parent 
the 4th circuit court disagreed 
we perceive no distinction between support derived directly 
from a fathers wages and support provided indirectly through 
social security the appeals court said the money to support the 
child comes directly through the father or indirectly through 
insurance he earned when working 
government lawyers said if the appeals courts view of the 
50disregard provision were adopted nationwide states and the 
federal government would have to pump 44 million more each year 
into the afdc program 
the 4th circuit courts ruling is binding law in virginia west 
virginia maryland north carolina and south carolina 
the government appeal noted that the 8th us circuit court of 
appeals has issued a ruling that conflicts with the 4th circuit 
court decision 
the case acted on today is sullivan vs stroop 89535 
</TEXT>
