<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed states to 
impose on airlines a tax partially based on flight time over the 
states 
the court without comment rejected a challenge to an oregon 
tax described by two airlines as a toll booth in the sky 
lawyers for alaska airlines and usair said oregon has erected 
a toll booth at 35000 feet for interstate airplanes wishing to 
pass over the state 
the formula for calculating an airlines property taxes includes 
the time an aircraft spends in the air over oregon even if the 
plane does not land or take off from there 
the two airlines said the tax for such flights almost doubles 
the amount they owe oregon each year alaska airlines said it 
amounted to an extra 750000 for 1988 
the oregon supreme court upheld the levy last february 
the state court said the tax is not an assessment on 
overflights more precisely the formula reflected that portion 
of time that each airlines aircraft property spent on the ground 
or in the air in oregon it said 
the state court also said there is an adequate connection 
between the tax and the benefits opportunities and protection 
conferred or afforded the airlines by the state the tax need 
not be assessed only as compensation for services provided it 
added 
the us supreme court justices since 1977 has allowed states to 
tax interstate business if the levy is fairly apportioned does 
not discriminate against interstate commerce and is fairly related 
to services which the state provides to the taxpayer 
alaska airlines and usair argued that oregon provides no 
services for overflights 
any monitoring of such flights is done by the federal 
government the airlines said any help the states might give for 
emergency landings is compensated by a part of the property tax 
assessed against schedued landings and departures they added 
both airlines have flights in and out of oregon and they did 
not challenge the portion of the property tax assessed against 
those flights 
but they said taxing aircraft simply because they have flown 
over that state violates the constitutions dueprocess 
guarantees and its protection for interstate commerce 
the airlines said wisconsin and pennsylvania have similar taxes 
the case is alaska airlines vs oregon 89346 
