<TEXT>
the supreme court today let federal officials 
place special limits on farmsupport payments for married couples 
the court without comment rejected a challenge to an 
agriculture department regulation that treats a husband and wife as 
one person when they apply for the payments 
the case stemmed from a department rule limiting how much money 
any person may receive in crop subsidies 
a group called women involved in farm economics or wife 
challenged the rule in 1988 when the maximum perperson payment 
was 50000 
wife founded in sidney neb in 1976 argued that married 
couples are barred unfairly from applying for two payments even 
though other farming partnerships are allowed to apply for multiple 
payments 
the regulation unfairly classified a husband and wife to be one 
person regardless of their separate interests and responsibilities 
the group said 
the us circuit court of appeals here upheld the regulation in 
june overruling a federal judge who had thrown it out 
the appeals court said treating a husband and wife as one person 
in such cases is reasonable because of their financial 
interdependence 
married couples as a group are more likely than other 
partners in farming enterprises to share completely in the products 
of their efforts the appeals court said 
the appeals court also noted that congress now permits a husband 
and wife to be treated as two people in special circumstances the 
amended law says couples may apply for double support payments if 
each engaged in unrelated farming operations prior to marriage and 
continue to operate separate farms during their marriage 
the case is wife vs yeutter 89366 
</TEXT>
