<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear a 
challenge to a federal law aimed at helping victims of crime 
recover their losses 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by a former post 
office worker in texas ordered to repay a bank 90412 he allegedly 
stole through credit card fraud the worker pleaded guilty to a 
single count of credit card fraud specifying only that more than 
1000 had been stolen 
frasiel l hughey worked at a post office in san antonio when he 
was indicted for mail theft and credit card fraud he pleaded 
guilty to one count of running up charges of more than 1000 on a 
mastercard issued by mbank usa to hershey godfrey 
the government said it had evidence hughey stole 21 cards issued 
by mbank and warned him he might be ordered to repay the bank 
147646 
hughey said he should be required to repay only 10422 the 
amount he said was charged to godfreys card 
a federal judge sentenced hughey to eight years in prison and 
ordered him to repay 90412 to mbank 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals upheld the restitution 
order last july 
the appeals court gave an expansive intrepretation to the 
federal victim and witness protection act 
at the minimum the law does not limit restitution to the 
amount specified in an indictment the appeals court said the 
restitution order in hugheys case had a significant connection 
with the conviction offense 
one of the principal purposes of the act was to ensure that 
wrongdoers to the degree possible make their victims whole if 
restitution were limited to the count of conviction given the high 
levels of plea bargaining within our criminal system in the 
majority of cases a victim could not be made whole the appeals 
court said 
the appeals court also rejected hugheys plea that he is too 
poor to pay 
the justice department urged the supreme court not to disturb 
the appeals court ruling the department said limiting the amount 
of restitution to the amount someone is convicted of stealing would 
violate congresss intent to compensate crime victims adequately 
the case is hughey vs us 895691 
</TEXT>
