<TEXT>
the supreme court today left it to a federal 
appeals court to take first crack at deciding whether louisianas 
system of higher education must undergo sweeping changes to help 
desegregate the states public colleges and universities 
the justices in a brief order said they do not yet have the 
authority to review the case the order means the case will proceed 
to the new orleansbased 5th us circuit court of appeals 
the justices last august blocked any ordered changes but 
todays action lifted that postponement enforcement of the 
desegregation plan envisioned by a threejudge federal court could 
begin unless the 5th circuit court grants a similar stay 
the threejudge courts july ruling would replace four governing 
boards with a single board over all public higher education in 
louisiana restrict admissions at some universities limit degree 
programs most schools can offer and establish a community college 
system 
the ruling also called for the gradual merging of the law 
schools at louisiana state university and southern university the 
states largest predominantly black school southerns 13000 
students attend three undergraduate campuses and the law school in 
baton rouge 
of the current four boards one governs the lsu system another 
governs the southern university system and a third oversees all 
other schools those three boards answer to the state board of 
trustees for higher education 
the present scheme has perpetuated illegal segregation in 
louisianas higher education the threejudge court ruled in a 
case begun in 1974 when justice department officials sued in 
behalf of black students 
the fourboard system has resulted in violations of a federal 
antidiscrimination law and the federal constitution the 
threejudge court said 
the lower court ordered designation of louisiana state 
university as the unified systems flagship school with the 
greatest number of graduate and research programs and the strictest 
admissions requirements 
it also called for creation of an intermediate level of four 
institutions including southern to offer significant doctoral and 
other graduate programs 
eight other schools including the predominantly black grambling 
state university would be designated as a third tier and limited 
to offering undergraduate degrees 
four colleges would become part of the new community college 
system 
court documents indicate that black enrollment at such 
historically white schools as lsu louisiana tech mcneese state 
nicholls state northeast louisiana and southeastern louisiana is 
less than 10 percent while blacks comprise over 99 percent of the 
enrollments at southern and grambling 
the threejudge courts ruling was appealed by the southern 
university board gov buddy roemers administration and attorney 
general william guste 
roemer and guste each said his appeal represented the states 
official views in the case and the governor in december asked 
the justices to dismiss gustes appeal 
the attorney generals appeal sought to have the threejudge 
courts ruling thrown out arguing that statistics alone on the 
race of students at each school cannot prove unlawful bias when 
each school is open to students of any race 
the governors appeal also argued that the threejudge court 
wrongly ruled that the state was guilty of unlawful bias but did 
not attack that portion of the lower courts order requiring one 
governing board 
roemer has been a champion of a singleboard system but has not 
been able to get the state legislature to go along with the idea 
the bush administration urged the justices to send the case to 
the 5th circuit court and not agree to handle an appeal directly 
from the threejudge court 
justice department lawyers argued that the case should have been 
handled by a lone trial judge and not the special threejudge court 
taking issue with that view roemer attorney john n kennedy 
told the justices all of higher education in louisiana is 
awaiting final resolution he urged the high court not to send 
the case to the 5th circuit court where any decision is likely to 
be appealed to the supreme court 
until this litigation is resolved kennedy said the 
operations of louisianas colleges and universities remains subject 
to extraordinary confusion and instability 
the cases are louisiana ex rel guste vs us 89556 southern 
university board of supervisors vs us 89557 and louisiana ex 
rel roemer vs us 89771 
</TEXT>
