<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to settle a 
conflict over the governments power to keep taxes withheld from 
businesses about to declare bankruptcy 
the court said it will hear an appeal by the trustee of bankrupt 
american international airways seeking to recover 700000 in taxes 
paid to the internal revenue service 
the airline company had become delinquent by the spring of 1984 
in withholding social security and income taxes from employee wages 
and excise taxes collected from passengers 
the irs then ordered the airline to file monthly instead of 
quarterly tax returns and open a special bank account to handle 
the tax deposits 
american international filed for bankruptcy on july 19 1984 to 
try and reorganize the business and pay off some of the money owed 
creditors that effort failed and three months later a trustee was 
appointed to liquidate the company 
the trustee sought to recover 16 million in taxes paid to the 
irs in the months leading up to the liquidation 
a bankruptcy judge in pennsylvania permitted the trustee to 
recover 700000 from the government and the irs appealed to the 
3rd us circuit court of appeals based in philadelphia 
the appeals court ruled last june that the trustee may not 
recover the 700000 the balance collected by the irs was not at 
issue in the decision 
the appeals court said that under federal law the withheld taxes 
must be considered placed in a special fund held in trust for the 
irs and are not part of the companys property protected by the 
bankruptcy proceedings 
the justice department asked the supreme court to take the case 
even though the governments position was upheld by the 3rd circuit 
court the department said another federal appeals court has issued 
a conflicting ruling and the high court should resolve the split 
the case is begier vs irs 89393 
</TEXT>
