<TEXT>
nasa conducted a stopandgo 
countdown and waited until the last possible minute monday before 
it knuckled under to clouds and scrubbed the launch of the space 
shuttle columbia for 24 hours 
nice try said launch director bob sieck 
the launch was rescheduled for 735 am tuesday 
air force weather officers had bet 8020 against weather 
permitting a launch monday but they said chances were 7030 that 
conditions would be favorable tuesday with a potential for low 
clouds and fog 
columbia with a fivemember crew is scheduled to spend 10 days 
in space to launch a navy communications satellite and to retrieve 
a bussize scientific satellite that will crash to earth in march 
if the rescue fails 
despite mondays rotten odds nasa officials decided to go 
through the complex launch routine on the slim chance of finding a 
hole in the clouds and also to exercise the refurbished facilities 
on launch pad 39a which had not been used in four years 
in fact the count was interrupted once while six 
troubleshooters checked a potential pressure problem with a valve 
system that sprays the launch pad with 300000 gallons of water 
just before liftoff the water absorbs the sound from the engines 
preventing it from bouncing back into the engines and causing 
damage 
the technicians determined that a zero pressure reading was 
false and that the system was ok 
nasa estimates that a launch abort on a weekday costs an extra 
624000 at the kennedy space center alone including 377000 in 
lost fuel there are additional costs at other nasa sites around 
the world the cost of a single shuttle launch is estimated between 
250 million and 300 million 
commander dan brandenstein and his crew had been strapped into 
their flight seats for nearly four hours while weather reports 
teetered between go and nogo finally mission control in houston 
radioed were not going to make it 
over the pad the sky was fairly clear but a 30milewide bank 
of clouds approaching from the west at 6000 feet would have made 
an emergency return difficult for brandenstein who would have to 
land the unpowered space ship on a concrete runway near the launch 
pad 
it was the fourth postponement for this particular mission but 
it was only the first time that astronauts were on board suited up 
and ready to go into space 
the mission is to be the first of 10 for 1990 the most for one 
year since the challenger explosion four years ago 
during their flight the astronauts first are to deploy a navy 
communications satellite 
then they are to chase capture and bring home a satellite 
called the long duration exposure facility or ldef the satellite 
essentially a 12sided frame is packed with 57 experiments many 
testing the ddurability of various materials exposed to space 
the satellite has spent nearly six years in orbit and if it 
isnt retrieved trackers estimate atmospheric drag will make it 
fall out of orbit and burn up about march 9 its experiments lost 
forever 
