<TEXT>
china has bought an additional 300000 metric 
tons of us wheat under a price subsidy program the agriculture 
department said monday 
f paul dickerson general sales manager for the departments 
foreign agricultural service said five private exporting companies 
made the deals under the departments export enhancement program 
or eep 
delivery of the wheat is schedfuled for may he said 
the sales were part of 1 million tons authorized for china under 
eep on dec 5 a previous allocation of 2 million tons made last 
feb 27 had been exhausted except for 10000 tons 
with the latest eep approvals china has 300000 tons remaining 
to be used under the current authorization 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat the latest sales would be about 11 million bushels at 
current prices estimated by usda at 383 per bushel the wheat 
would have a farm value of around 42 million 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in 
selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged 1545 per ton or 
about 42 cents per bushel 
the subsidized sales were handled by bunge corp 85000 tons 
peavey co 80000 cargill inc 50000 j aron amp co 45000 
and tradigrain inc 40000 
with the latest sales china has bought about 54 million tons 
of us wheat for delivery in the 198990 marketing year which 
began june 1 most of it without subsidies in 198889 china 
bought more than 8 million tons of us wheat all of it under the 
eep program 
