<TEXT>
president bush struck a combative stance 
for the 1990 congressional session monday complaining it is past 
time for lawmakers to approve a capital gains tax cut and other 
white house proposals left hanging last year 
saying a capital gains bill would be a top priority bush 
declared i am sick and tired of the demagogues who call this a 
tax cut for the rich it means jobs it means savings and it is 
good for all americans 
many democrats in congress have opposed a reduction on grounds 
the chief beneficiaries would be the wealthy 
bush spelled out his legislative hopes in a speech to 8000 
delegates to the annual convention of the american farm bureau the 
nations largest farm organization with 38 million member families 
he also called for action on anticrime and cleanair 
legislation but the tax cut talk won the loudest applause from 
farmers bush reminded his audience that lower tax rates would 
apply to the sale of farmland 
on a separate issue bush also won cheers by saying i am 
mighty proud of the american forces who were sent to panama to 
depose manuel antonio noriega 
noriega is being held in miami on drugtrafficking charges and 
bush said the joy shown by the people of panama says it all 
the capital gains legislation concerns taxes on profits derived 
from the sale of stocks real estate and other assets bush has 
proposed lowering the top tax rate to 15 percent from the current 
tops of 28 percent and 33 percent 
a bushbacked plan was defeated last year when senate 
republicans could not muster the 60 votes necessary to break a 
democratic filibuster against it but lawmakers on both sides of 
the issue have expressed doubt that procedural devices could kill 
the proposal this year 
an aide to senate majority leader george mitchell who led the 
opposition last year said monday the maine democrat supported a 
capital gains tax reduction in 1986 and has said he will 
continue to support one if it meets three criteria if it doesnt 
adversely effect the budget deficit if it is targeted and if it 
is part of a fair and progressive tax structure 
one of every four democrats sided with republicans when the 
house voted for a capital gains cut last september but even some 
democrats who are longtime supporters of lower capitalgains taxes 
were unhappy with the bill because it would have provided a lower 
tax rate for only 2 years and then would have substituted a system 
under which gains caused by inflation would be excluded from 
taxation 
bush has not disclosed details of the cut he will propose in his 
jan 29 budget message however congressional republicans say they 
expect him to call for a plan that would provide a greater tax 
incentive the longer an asset is held thus profits from the sale 
of property owned for five years would be taxed less than would 
gains from something owned two years 
present law taxes capital gains at the same rates as other 
income 
the fight isnt over yet bush said contending that a 
capital gains tax cut would help keep american agriculture 
dynamic and prosperous 
more generally bush recalled that i put out my hand to the 
congress to the democratic majority in his inaugural address a 
year ago and offered lawmakers proposals on crime clean air and 
the capital gains tax cut 
now a year has past the new year is upon us and its time it 
is past time for congress to tend to some of the unfinished 
business bush said 
with congress due back in session jan 23 bush said the hand 
of cooperation is once again extended and i would only add 
america wants it done right america wants it done responsibly and 
america wants it done now 
after his speech bush toured futuristic exhibits of 
hightechnology agriculture at walt disneys epcot center he also 
visited the living seas building and came face to face with 
porpoises and scuba divers in a tank 
the trip came at the start of a year in which congress must 
update the 1985 farm legislation that reduced basic crop price 
supports saving billions of dollars for taxpayers 
crop subsidies this year are expected to total about 11 
billion far below the record 26 billion in 1986 
providing only a hint about the farm bill he will propose bush 
said we must have marketoriented farm policies that allow 
producers more flexibility to decide what crops to grow 
at the same time weve got to maintain a safety net to 
protect farmers from conditions beyond their control the 
president said 
moreover bush said weve got to expand markets and enhance 
productivity weve got to assure the public that americas food is 
the safest in the world and weve got to protect our precious 
environment 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter has said he does not 
expect massive changes in the 1985 law but has acknowledged that 
the 1990 rewrite must tackle the issues of environmental and food 
safety 
bush said international markets for farmers are improving with 
us agricultural exports increasing last year for the third year 
in a row 
we also support expanding our ties with eastern europe and the 
soviet union to open even more markets bush said noting that 
yeutter led a delegation to poland to suggest ways it could shift 
to a market economy 
were forging new partnerships between our agriculture 
industries and eastern europes emerging economies 
