relatives of charles stuart who might have 
suspected he was involved in his wifes killing had no legal 
obligation under state law to report that to police legal experts 
say 
in massachusetts persons are criminally culpable for what 
they do for their acts not for what they know said frank 
chubert a professor of criminal justice at northeastern university 
in boston 
the issue was raised last week when stuarts youngest brother 
matthew implicated him in his pregnant wifes shooting death oct 
23 matthew stuart told police he disposed of a gun and her purse 
at his brothers request 
charles stuart apparently aware he had become a suspect 
committed suicide thursday as police sought to arrest him he had 
told police that a mugger shot him and his wife during a robbery 
after they left a hospital childbirth class 
matthew stuart reportedly told others of his suspicions 
legal experts say that although some people might have known the 
truth all along they cannot be held criminally liable under 
massachusetts law for withholding information 
there is no obligation said john dawley who was charles 
stuarts attorney but morally and ethically there are different 
standards 
about a dozen states but not massachusetts have good 
samaritan laws that require people to tell authorities if they 
know a crime has been committed said charles ogletree a professor 
at harvard law school but he said the law is rarely enforced 
its hard to persuade a jury to convict someone who said i 
saw a crime and i was scared to report it ogletree said in an 
interview friday 
also if such laws were strictly enforced they could have 
painful implications chubert said 
just think of where that goes he said does that mean mom 
and dad get prosecuted for failure to report you could use the 
power to lock up a persons family 
massachusetts also grants immunity for close relatives who 
become an accessory to a crime after the criminal act has been 
committed ogletree said typically he said immunity would be 
granted to a relative who hides a fugitive 
but in the case of matthew stuart the issue of legal protection 
might be more complicated experts said 
his attorney said matthew stuart at his brothers instruction 
met him the night of the shooting and took a bag containing a gun 
and mrs stuarts purse 
an important part of his story is that he wasnt aware mrs 
stuart was shot when he retrieved the items if in fact he knew 
that the crime was being committed then he might be crossing the 
line into aiding the crime in which he would not have the 
immunity ogletree said 
hes on thin ice said joseph balliro a criminal lawyer in 
boston thats going to be up to a grand jury to decide if they 
believe him or not believe him 
furthermore experts said the disposal of a gun can be 
considered a separate crime such as obstruction of justice 
if he goes out and hides the evidence of a crime then thats 
a nono balliro said friday 
john julian a spokesman for the suffolk county district 
attorneys office said friday he could not comment on whether 
stuart might be charged or receive immunity there is an ongoing 
grand jury investigation he said 
