<TEXT>
the computer tampering trial of an ivy 
league student accused of crippling thousands of computers 
nationwide opened monday with jury selection and federal 
prosecutors seeking to limit defense evidence 
opening arguments were to begin tuesday morning in the us 
district court trial of robert t morris jr a 24yearold 
suspended cornell university graduate student 
the arnold md man is the first person to come to trial under 
the 1986 computer fraud and abuse act if convicted he faces up to 
five years in prison and a 250000 fine 
morris is accused of designing and setting loose a socalled 
worm program that replicated wildly immobilizing an estimated 
6000 computers linked to the internet research computer network 
including those at air force and national aeronautics and space 
administration facilities 
in a motion filed monday justice department lawyers sought to 
hinder morris expected defense that he did not intend to paralyze 
the computer network by allegedly introducing a rogue program into 
it on nov 2 1988 
the prosecutors asked judge howard munson to limit examination 
of witnesses on morris state of mind specifically whether it was 
his intent to prevent authorized use of internet and to cause any 
loss or damage to the system 
the evidence of lack of intent to cause loss or lack of 
intent to prevent the authorized use of the victim computers 
however is simply not relevant to any issue in this case the 
motion said 
munson did not immediately rule on the motion but when defense 
attorney thomas guidoboni raised the question of intent in a 
pretrial motion to have morris indictment dismissed munson 
rejected the argument that the defendants intentions were 
pertinent to the indictments legality 
guidoboni contends the law is unclear as to whether criminal 
intent means intent to cause damage or simply intent to gain access 
to computer systems 
justice department attorneys ellen r meltzer and mark d rasch 
declined to comment on their own motion outside the courtroom 
the first 10 potential jurors questioned from a pool of 93 were 
dismissed due to objections by munson or lawyers but all parties 
were able to agree on the next 12 candidates finishing jury 
selection in less than three hours 
morris who was a firstyear doctoral student in computer 
studies before his suspension sat attentively as lawyers 
questioned potential jurors his father robert t morris sr 
chief scientist at the national computer security center in 
bethesda md and mother also attended 
prosecutors also asked the court to allow witnesses to explain 
what the worm program was designed to do 
evidence that morris designed earlier versions of the computer 
virus are relevant to the charges the government said in its 
motion the earlier versions were not launched 
the trial is expected to last about two weeks the government 
presented the court with a potential list of about 20 witnesses 
and guidoboni named at least four witnesses in court 
a cornell university commission concluded that morris was guilty 
of reckless disregard for creating the program although the 
university commission found him responsible morris has never 
publicly admitted creating the worm program or introducing it into 
internet 
