<TEXT>
western nations alarmed at a buildup of 
longrange missiles in the middle east imposed restrictions on the 
sale of sensitive equipment to third world countries but iraq is 
exploiting loopholes in those controls to develop a formidable 
missile arsenal 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
despite efforts of industrialized nations 
to curtail a missile buildup in the middle east iraq is building 
an advanced arms industry with help from a network of hightech 
companies in the west 
iraq announced in december that it had launched a 48ton 
threestage rocket capable of putting a satellite in space and 
testfired two surfacetosurface missiles with a range of 1240 
miles 
us officials confirmed the dec 5 launch but did not say what 
type of missile was used 
industrialized nations alarmed at the arms buildup in the 
middle east have curbed the sale of sensitive equipment such as 
stateoftheart computers guidance systems heatresistant 
materials and computercontrolled machinery to third world 
countries 
but iraq has exploited loopholes in the controls imposed by the 
united states britain west germany france italy canada and 
japan in the missile technology control regime of 1987 
iraq iran syria saudi arabia and libya are all missile powers 
now all except libya have weapons capable of hitting cities in 
israel 
with superpower detente diminishing the threat of a ussoviet 
conflict analysts fear the most dangerous threat is now posed by 
the spread of longrange missiles in the third world 
one of the key weapons in president saddam husseins effort to 
make iraq the major regional power is a twostage ballistic 
missile the condor 2 capable of delivering nuclear or chemical 
warheads 
iraq has been developing the condor 2 with argentina and egypt 
since 1984 
iraqs arms industry is quite advanced now and saddam is 
certainly determined to build his missiles said hansheino 
kopietz a middle east analyst with londons international 
institute for strategic studies 
from what weve been able to determine the iraqis are capable 
of producing condor 2 but they still lack a reliable guidance 
system kopietz said in a telephone interview theyve been 
trying to get one from the germans 
some analysts believe iraq may be able to testfire a condor 2 
prototype in the next year or two 
israel claims iraq already has an accurate guidance system even 
so one israeli source said condor 2 was a long way from being 
deployed 
the iraqis are negotiating with brazils space agency for 
satellite technology under a 50 million deal analysts say 
ozilio silva director of the brazilian agency and a former 
president of brazils embraer aircraft manufacturer visited 
baghdad earlier this year and a team of iraqi scientists was in rio 
de janeiro last may 
france iraqs second biggest arms supplier after the soviet 
union sent an aerospace industry team to baghdad in november to 
discuss cooperation 
iraqs drive to build up its own defense industry like irans 
was spurred by the 8year persian gulf war it was the first 
conflict in which the belligerents hammered each others cities 
with missiles 
until recently many military analysts scoffed at iraqs claims 
it could produce advanced weapons systems 
but the iraqis unveiled a wide range of technology at the 
baghdad arms fair in april it included the lion of babylon tank a 
locally assembled soviet t72 that included systems developed by 
iraqi engineers and several missiles apparently modeled on soviet 
systems 
iraqi officials defend efforts to develop an arms industry by 
citing the threat from iran despite last years ceasefire in the 
war 
londons financial times quoted salah almoukhtar 
directorgeneral of iraqs information ministry as saying the 
only solution to the threat to our very existence is to establish 
our own military industry and provide our armed forces with iraqi 
arms 
like other iraqi officials he declined to discuss iraqs 
purchasing network beyond saying baghdad will get the technology 
it needs anywhere it can 
the iraqi network came to light in august when the us federal 
reserve found that the atlanta branch of italys banca nazionale de 
lavoro had extended unauthorized credit of nearly 3 billion to 
iraq since february 1988 
