<TEXT>
hes a lifelong mormon who writes about the 
people he knows best fellow members of the church of jesus christ 
of latterday saints neal chandler concedes he has a limited 
audience mormon attitudes toward fiction being what they are and 
nonmormons cant relate to what hes writing about but profit is 
not his motive 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
neal chandler knows he wont get rich or 
famous writing stories about mormons for one thing he says most 
mormons dont read fiction 
but chandler gets his reward in the winces or belly laughs of 
recognition he elicits from the few who do 
ive been told by many people that im wasting time and talent 
on mormon culture says chandler coordinator of the creative 
writing program at cleveland state university in ohio 
chandler a lifelong mormon doesnt agree 
its my resource and its a rich one he says and to 
turn away from it for marketing reasons seems just strange to me i 
cannot even conceive of doing it i know a great deal about 
mormonism and i care a great deal about these things these 
people 
chandlers first book a collection of 15 stories titled 
benediction was published recently by the university of utah 
press as part of its mormon studies series 
some of the story titles betray chandlers aim to illuminate 
often with humor what he describes as that middle place between 
us and the larger american culture they include the 
righteousness hall of fame mormon tabernacle blues and the 
only divinely authorized plan for financial success in this life or 
the next 
in the latter a mormon woman justifies involvement in a pyramid 
scheme by pointing out the pyramid on the back of a dollar bill as 
signifying christian capitalism mandated by the founding 
fathers 
after chandlers story benediction was published in a mormon 
journal in 1985 he received a call late at night from a man he 
barely knew who said hed just read the story his wife was now 
reading it the man said and she was laughing so hard she wet 
her pants 
it doesnt strike nonmormons the same way because they have 
no way of relating to it chandler says 
chandler realizes his audience will be narrow because only a 
small percentage of the worlds 67 million mormons are 
intellectuals and only a fraction of those read fiction 
mormons even intellectual mormons are so concerned about 
being taken seriously that they take themselves terribly 
seriously chandler says and fiction seems to most of them to 
violate that tendency even among people who read and are educated 
it doesnt seem somehow to be respectable 
for example chandler says people come up to him and say 
hey i read your article that used to strike him as odd no 
more 
ive just come to the conclusion that story while im sure 
it is a word that is included in their vocabulary is not somehow 
emotionally includable he says the term that seems 
respectable is article 
chandler 47 does not have to rely on flights of fancy for his 
glimpses of mormon life in the late 20th century he was born and 
raised a mormon in salt lake city he served a 2year church 
mission in northern germany and has lived mostly outside utah since 
i think the truth is that when the stories seem the most 
outrageous they are most likely to be grounded in real 
experience says chandler the sunday school superintendent in 
his shaker heights ohio congregation 
he believes that since the church of jesus christ of latterday 
saints shed its polygamist roots and began after world war ii to 
gain respectability its members have become increasingly confused 
about who they are as they embrace nonmormon ideals in business 
and other fields 
mormons he says like to think of themselves as the 
quintessential americans but i think in the long term we cant be 
that and preserve ourselves as the religiously motivated energized 
and guided culture that we need to be 
chandler is careful to draw a distinction between utah mormons 
with pioneer ancestry and mormons elsewhere the former he says 
sort of sense themselves as a kind of mormon nobility and 
aristocracy when they go out to the rest of the church they go out 
as ambassadors in a sense 
and so there is in the mission field a sense of inferiority 
against that kind of background 
chandler plans other writing projects not all of them 
mormonrelated including a political novel and another book of 
stories but his most ambitious work will be a novel set in central 
utah for which he will draw on historical mythical and folklore 
sources 
