<TEXT>
years of national economic decline 
have plunged brazils educational system into a crisis that 
officials fear will deprive the country of the brainpower needed to 
ensure social stability in the future 
illiteracy is creeping back up the student dropout rate is 
rising and schools are forced to close for lack of money schools 
that survive are turning out illinformed unskilled graduates the 
officials say 
a small elite of college graduates frustrated by shrinking job 
markets is fleeing the country to pursue postgraduate degrees and 
jobs in the united states and europe a brain drain expected to 
hinder brazils development for decades 
dr paulo alvim secretary general of the education ministry 
estimates that the deteriorating system will adversely affect the 
quality of the labor pool and slow the nations progress in 
scientific fields 
the educational deterioration has a devastating social 
impact alvim added young people are losing touch with society 
and their leaders leading them into the black holes of drugs 
alcohol and crime by allowing our school system to deteriorate we 
are in effect creating a marginal population that will eventually 
strain the governments social programs 
the rising cost of education even though teachers salaries 
remain low is another area of difficulty 
last year students protesting tuition increases clashed with 
police in major cities 
the system simply cant get any worse than it is now weve 
hit absolute rock bottom said fatima cunha secretary general of 
education in rio de janeiro state 
according to a united nations survey brazil which has the 
western worlds eighthlargest economy has one of the highest 
illiteracy rates in south america 27 percent in 1988 up from 25 
percent in 1986 it is believed to have risen even further in 1989 
brazil a nation of 150 million people had been making headway 
against illiteracy 
according to alvim illiteracy in brazil had been declining 
progressively since 1872 when the rate was 83 percent fifty 
percent of the population was illiterate in 1950 in 1960 40 
percent of brazilians were illiterate 
a unicef study released in december said brazil had the seventh 
highest grade school dropout rate in the world behind only haiti 
yemen chad the central african republic bangladesh and burma it 
said only 23 percent of pupils completed grade school in 198587 
although the law requires children to remain in school until they 
are 18 
about 27 million elementary school students are attending 
private and public schools nationwide only 34 million students 
attend public and private high schools and 15 million are enrolled 
in private and public universities 
a recent survey by the brazilian institute of public opinion and 
statistics found other dark spots in the educational system 
eleven percent of high school teachers have not finished grade 
school in several states in the poor northeast the rate is 40 
percent 
nearly threequarters of the countrys school buildings are 
unfit for use 
blame for the crisis is placed essentially on brazils plunge 
since the mid1970s into the worst economic crisis in its history 
it now has a 110 billion foreign debt a 1765 percent annual 
inflation rate and an economy in stagnation 
the government spends just 28 percent of revenue on education 
roughly the equivalent of 98 billion compared with an average 
of 4 percent in the rest of latin america 
the us federal outlay for education not counting state and 
municipal expenditures was about 22 billion for 1988 
even though brazilian government outlays for education already 
were low officials recently cut by 40 percent the money allocated 
for public universities and special education programs and federal 
funds often get lost in huge state bureaucracies and never reach 
the classroom secretary general cunha of the rio ministry said 
presidentelect fernando collor de mello a conservative who 
takes office march 15 has pledged to build schools and spend more 
on education but with 90 percent of federal revenues now earmarked 
for government employees salaries there isnt much likely to be 
available anytime soon for schools 
grammar and high school teachers in major cities earn the 
equivalent of 100 a month in outlying areas of the poor 
northeast such as in the village of jerumenha in maranhao state 
grade school teachers make just 6 a month 
many teachers give extra night classes to make extra money 
others sell perfume jewelry and jeans in school hallways during 
class breaks 
its hard to look your students in the eye afterwards said 
maria luiza de vitergo 29 a high school history teacher youre 
supposed to be their role model not a peddler 
</TEXT>
