<TEXT>
war and natures caprice are conspiring to 
create food shortages that again threaten millions of people with 
starvation in ethiopia and sudan 
drought and the depredations wrought by two long civil wars have 
imperiled as many as 4 million people in northern ethiopia 
according to relief officials there 
similarly in neighboring sudan where as many as 250000 died of 
hunger in 198788 a resumption of fighting in a 6yearold civil 
war has raised fresh fears of another famine despite an extensive 
and by all accounts successful united nationsled relief 
operation last year 
men at war not nature have become the biggest threat to those 
in need with governments and guerrillas preventing a helpful 
international community from getting food to hungry peasants 
holding back the relief effort in ethiopia is the governments 
resistance to delivering food to people behind rebel lines in the 
rebellious province of eritrea and most particularly in the 
province of tigre leaving an untold number of people beyond the 
reach of aid agencies 
diplomats and relief workers fear that if a way is not found to 
feed these people ethiopia could suffer a repeat of the great 
famine of 198485 when as many as 1 million people died 
it has the potential if nothing is done about it said david 
morton the un world food programs representative in ethopia 
if food is not gotten in there in some way everyone is 
concerned well have a famine situation resulting from a drought 
situation said morton we cant say how many would die because 
we still dont know how many are affected but clearly very large 
numbers 
the united nations has appealed for an initial 700000 tons of 
emergency food aid about a third of which has been pledged by 
foreign donors more food may be needed if later assessments show 
the situation worsening 
morton says his agency recently began moving 60000 tons to 
distribution points in the northernmost province of eritrea much 
of which still remains in government hands 
tigre eritreas southern neighbor is the main problem morton 
says 
the province home to an estimated 26 million people is 
entirely in rebel hands and consequently inaccessible to relief 
agencies 
the rebel tigre peoples liberation front which has been 
fighting since 1975 to oust president mengistu haile mariam gained 
control of its home province early last year since august the 
rebels have made their greatest gains pushing southward and 
westward into neighboring provinces and moving ever closer to 
ethiopias capital addis ababa 
ethiopia has conscripted hundreds of thousands of men to fight 
the tigrean rebels who pose the greatest military threat to 
mengistus government 
relief officials nonetheless say they are encouraged by the 
governments recent request that several indigenous relief and 
church agencies study ways to get food to those behind rebel lines 
in tigre and report on their findings 
however there is the lurking fear that the government is not 
sincere about wanting to feed those it considers the rebels 
support base 
limited amounts of food can be moved to tigre through 
neighboring sudan 
but aid officials express a concern that if food shipments are 
not begun soon peasants will begin long and treacherous walks 
across embattled barren territory in search of food at 
governmentsanctioned distribution centers outside tigre 
weakened by their migration and lack of food and unable to 
return home the peasants could create vast overcrowded and 
unhygenic famine camps similar to those of 198485 in which more 
people died of disease than of starvation 
similar fears surrounded the 198788 relief operation when crop 
failures also threatened millions with starvation but during that 
emergency the government still had control of some of tigre and 
much of eritrea and food got through to those in need before mass 
migrations began 
we cant avoid drought but we can avoid famine morton said 
longterm prospects however are not encouraging 
weve got a situation of increasing population year after year 
and stagnant production of food said one aid official who spoke 
on condition of anonymity the longterm outlook on present 
trends isnt good 
in southern sudan the resumption of fighting between the rebel 
sudan peoples liberation army and the government has derailed 
relief efforts credited with averting a repeat of the 1988 tragedy 
observers say the nearly 100000 tons of food ferried into the 
embattled region between april and november through corridors of 
tranquility staved off widespread death 
both warring parties declared a series of ceasefires to permit 
the shipments however that informal truce broke down in late 
october when fighting flared and in early november the government 
declared a ban on all relief flights saying it wanted to 
investigate the aerial bombing of a rebelheld town the sudan 
rebels have no planes 
bombings have continued in many southern towns being helped by 
the united nations and the government never happy about food being 
given to areas under the rebels control has accused relief 
workers of delivering arms ammunition and spare parts under the 
cover of humanitarian aid 
although sudans military leadership has promised a conference 
to consider allowing the resumption of relief flights aid workers 
fear the worst 
unless we continue our efforts through the next season 
southern sudan could fall back to a lifethreatening situation 
said vincent oreilly spokesman for the unled operation 
lifeline sudan 
ironically nature has provided the region with plenty of rain 
given tools and seeds the peasants could grow nearly twice as 
much food this year as was delivered by the emergency operation 
oreilly said 
in its second phase he added operation lifeline sudan planned 
to deliver 2 million worth of seeds and hand tools but the 
fighting has made this impossible leaving the region in a perilous 
state he said 
the food deliveries have maintained people in place 
oreilly said we have not addressed the underlying agricultural 
problem and the impact of the war 
unless we do we could face a return to a famine situation 
</TEXT>
