<TEXT>
you dont necessarily give up your children as 
dependents for tax purposes just because they have jobs of their 
own 
it depends on their income and living expenses 
each dependent claimed can reduce taxes by 560 for someone in 
the 28 percent bracket but the rules for qualifying can be so 
complicated that many taxpayers miss the chance to make claims to 
which they are entitled 
there are five basic tests for determining whether someone is 
your dependent all five must be met 
relationship a dependent must have lived with you throughout 
1989 except for being temporarily absent for school military 
service vacation or illness or must be a relative relative 
includes child grandchild stepchild parent grandparent 
brother sister uncle aunt nephew niece or inlaw livein 
lover yes so long as the relationship does not violate local law 
income generally a dependent must have gross income under 
2000 not counting such taxexempt income as welfare benefits or 
the nontaxable portion of social security note that is gross 
income for example an elderly parent who made 2500 in a 
parttime job would not qualify even if expenses of earning that 
money reduced net income below 2000 
the rules are more liberal where your children are concerned 
there is no limit to the income your child may earn and still 
qualify as your dependent if 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
he or she was under 19 at the end of 1989 or 
he or she was a fulltime student and under 24 last year 
fulltime means enrolled with a full class load during any five 
months of the year a government onfarm training course also 
qualifies 
citizenship the dependent must be a us citizen or resident 
alien or a resident of canada or mexico your adopted child need 
not be a us citizen but could have lived with you in 1989 in a 
foreign country 
no joint return a married person you claim as a dependent may 
not file a joint return again there is an exception if neither 
spouse is required to file but a joint return is filed to get a 
refund of withheld taxes you may claim the dependent 
support you must have provided more than half the dependents 
financial support last year 
first the exceptions if you and someone else together pay more 
than half the support of a dependent but no one exceeds 50 percent 
you may claim the dependent by contributing more than 10 percent 
and having the others sign form 2120 multiple support declaration 
in case of divorce or separation if you are the parent without 
custody of a child you may list the child as a dependent if the 
other parent agrees in writing to give up the claim or if a 
pre1985 agreement or decree gave you the right to claim the child 
to figure whether the support test was met you will have to 
determine what the dependent received from other sources including 
his or her own income and note that although nontaxable income 
does not figure into the calculation of the dependents income 
mantioned above it does count here that is taxexempt interest 
for example must be included when the dependent calculates total 
resources used for his or her own support 
some items of support are obvious shelter food clothing 
transportation including purchase of a car medical expenses 
including insurance education and childcare services 
other items that might be overlooked include charitable 
contributions on behalf of the dependent cosmetics pets toys 
tobacco beer gifts spending money and even the cost of a 
wedding 
you may not count as support such items as life insurance 
premiums scholarships and income and social security taxes 
remember that any dependent 2 or older must have a social 
security number which must be entered on your tax return obtain a 
number by filing form ss5 with the social security administration 
if you have mailed that form but havent received a number by the 
time you are ready to file your tax return write applied for 
on line 6c column 3 
