<TEXT>
despite the best efforts of congress to move 
more taxpayers to the standard deduction itemizing is still a 
better deal for millions of couples and individuals 
unless other considerations such as time recordkeeping and 
general frustration are more important than money you should 
itemize if your deductions exceed the standard deduction that is 
5200 for a couple filing a joint return 3100 for a single 
person 4550 for a qualified head of household and 2600 for a 
married person filing separately 
congress reduced or eliminated some widely used deductions as 
the price for cutting tax rates across the board in the 1986 tax 
overhaul because of those changes the share of tax returns 
itemizing deductions dropped from 395 percent in 1987 to 333 
percent in 1988 
that percentage probably fell again on returns filed last year 
because of a continuing phaseout of the deduction for consumer 
interest that deduction which includes automobile and education 
loans and creditcard interest dropped to 20 percent in 1989 will 
be 10 percent for interest paid this year and will reach zero in 
1991 
for most people the biggest deduction is for home mortgage 
interest and remains unchanged from last year your mortgage 
interest is fully deductible if 
the mortgages on your principal home were taken out on or 
before oct 13 1987 or 
any mortgages taken out after that date were used only to buy 
build or improve your principal home and they totaled 1 million or 
less in all of 1989 or if 
any mortgages taken out after that date were used for purposes 
other than home purchase building or improvement and totaled 
100000 or less last year 
publication 936 free from the irs will be helpful if part of 
your mortgage is not deductible or if you own two or more homes 
points paid to obtain a mortgage may be deducted fully in one 
year only if the loan was used to buy or improve your main home and 
the home was used as security you paid the points from funds other 
than the loan if points are customarily charged in your area and 
if what you paid is not out of line with the usual fee 
otherwise the points must be deducted gradually over the life 
of the loan 
other deductions 
medical unreimbursed medical expenses that exceed 7 percent of 
adjusted gross income these can range from the usual fees paid to 
physicians dentists and christian science practitioners but not 
scientology counselors to prescribed exercise equipment limited 
lodging expenses for outoftown care and sometimes even the cost 
of a wig 
contributions donations to irsrecognized charities generally 
are fully deductible if total contributions are no more than 50 
percent of adjusted gross income you may deduct up to 30 percent 
of agi for contributions of money or ordinaryincome property as 
opposed to property that could produce a capital gain use form 
8283 to report gifts other than money when the value exceeds 500 
no breakdown is required on your return if such gifts are worth 
500 or less 
taxes there is no longer a deduction for sales taxes but you 
still may write off state and local income and real estate taxes 
personalproperty taxes for cars boats and the like are deductible 
if based on value and not on weight excises tolls fines license 
fees and estate taxes are not deductible 
moving you may be able to deduct certain expenses of a 
jobrelated move if the new job is at least 35 miles farther from 
your old home than was the old job for example if your old job 
was three miles from home your new job must be at least 38 miles 
from the old home if you had no previous job the new job must be 
35 miles or more from your old home publication 521 free from the 
irs gives details 
losses nonbusiness losses due to fire theft storm and 
similar events may be deductible but misplacing or breaking a 
valuable item is not a deductible loss after absorbing the first 
100 of each loss you may deduct only the total amount of all 
uninsured losses in a year that exceeds 10 percent of adjusted 
gross income see form 4684 
miscellaneous most expenses relating to your employment union 
dues tools and work clothes not suitable for street wear 
investments advice safedeposit box subscriptions or tax 
preparation are deductible only to the extent they exceed 2 percent 
of adjusted gross income although you still may be able to write 
off a second phone in your home or longdistance charges a 
deduction is no longer allowed for the basic monthly charge for the 
first phone in your home 
</TEXT>
