the search for simplicity is leading more and 
more taxpayers to file the singlepage form 1040ez 
that is not a wise choice for many taxpayers you could save 
money by filing form 1040a or the long form 1040 
here are the basic rules 
1040ez only for single taxpayers who are neither blind nor past 
their 65th birthday and had taxable income after subtracting the 
standard deduction and the 2000 exemption of less than 50000 
all the income except up to 400 of interest must have been from 
wages tips or taxable scholarships 
1040a for any filing status same income ceiling as 1040ez 
except you may include interest and dividends up to the 50000 
limit and and unemployment compensation you may use 1040a and 
still claim an individual retirement account deduction the 
childcare credit or the earnedincome credit 
1040 any taxpayer may use it 
there are no supplemental forms and schedules for 1040ez the 
1040a uses only schedule 1 for interest dividends and the 
childcare credit here are some of the most widely used forms and 
schedules to accompany 1040 if not included in your tax 
instructions they are available by calling irs 
schedule c to report profit or loss from your business 
schedule d for capital gains and losses 
schedule e for rent royalties and partnership income and 
expenses 
schedule f for farm income and expenses 
schedule r for claiming the credit for elderly or disabled 
schedule se to calculate social security selfemployment tax 
form 2106 for employee business expenses 
form 2119 to report the sale of your home 
form 3903 for jobrelated moving expenses 
form 4868 to get an automatic fourmonth extension for time to 
file your return but not to pay any tax owed 
form 8283 to list noncash charitable contributions that total 
more than 500 
