<TEXT>
no matter what you make if youre able to put aside anything 
for savings youre proabably in a tax bracket that will make 
taxfree municipal bonds attractive says a specialist in these 
issues 
michael s appelbaum first vice president at shearson lehman 
hutton in new york city advises wage earners to balance these safe 
investments with higher yielding taxable moneymarket instruments 
municipals he points out are backed by the taxing power of 
cities and states and are among the safest investments around 
second only the us government bonds 
appelbaum notes that it doesnt take a huge income to end up in 
the top tax brackets for example a working couple filing a joint 
return of 29751 net taxable income in new york state but not 
living in new york city which has its own tax are in the combined 
federal and new york state tax bracket of 337 percent another 
couple in the same locale filing a joint return on 71901 will be 
in the top combined 386 percent bracket 
if youre in that top combined bracket and find an investment 
paying 9 percent youll end up with only 58 percent after paying 
out federal and state taxes on the investment in contrast a 
municipal bond might pay you 7 or 8 percent free of both federal 
and state taxes 
throughout the country even in states without income taxes 
the general rule is that 7 percent to 8 percent tax free in the top 
33 percent federal income tax bracket is like 104 percent to 119 
percent from a bank or other taxable investment says appelbaum 
he says the ratio between municipal bonds at 8 percent and 
taxable ginnie maes from the government national mortgage 
association at 10 percent works out to about 80 percent even 
though the municipal bond ostensibly pays 20 percent less than the 
ginnie mae in every tax bracket above 20 percent the takehome 
pay from the municipal bond beats the ginnie 
when choosing a bond appelbaum recommends looking at other 
factors besides the yield percentage if you need a bond you can 
cash in within a few years instead of letting it mature for 10 or 
20 years youll have to give up some yield if you want current 
income to live on and the best payout now then get the bonds with 
the highest interest rates he says youll get maximum return on 
your savings each time you clip a coupon or receive semiannual 
interest though you may have to pay a premium 
appelbaum suggests you consult with your accountant financial 
advisor or broker when picking bonds so they can recommend buys 
based on your needs some of the questions youll be considering 
when do you plan to retire do you have heirs how much are secure 
triplea ratings worth to you in cold cash are the bonds to be a 
gift are they for your childrens education are they being used 
to build up your estate are you living on the interest and will 
you leave the principal to your survivors should you reduce your 
estate and your estate taxes through an orderly invasion of your 
capital when do you need or want your principal back do you need 
income to live on spend or enjoy or are you in a position to 
defer current income and take a big lump sum when bonds mature 
appelbaum says resale of bonds before maturity will be affected 
by market conditions but points out that municipal bonds assure you 
of getting interest all along and your principal at the end 
