<TEXT>
in the wake of the 1986 tax reform act insurance investments 
may be among the few which offer safe and substantial tax 
advantages 
annuities and whole life insurance earn interest for investors 
and provide taxfree dividends or taxdeferred growth says peter 
goodstein senior vice president of kornreich insurance services 
he advises investors to include both as longterm investments in 
their overall financial plans 
the tax benefits of both whole life insurance and annuities 
are hard to duplicate in other longterm investments says 
goodstein unlike taxfree bonds and mutual funds the underlying 
guaranteed value of insurance products doesnt fluctuate with the 
market so in many ways its a safer investment 
he points out that whole life insurance lets the investor 
accumulate cash which can remain liquid without penalty and in 
addition his death benefit can be structured so that his 
beneficiaries can receive policy proceeds tax free the cost of 
whole life insurance however must cover administration costs 
in contrast annuities are noload investments that sometimes 
have greater yields than treasuries or bank certificates of 
deposit however annuities are usually not structured as liquid 
assets and carry withdrawal penalties for investors under the age 
of 59 these might include a 10 percent penalty imposed by the 
irs the proceeds taxed as ordinary income and a further penalty 
by the insurance company 
goodstein says that as whole life insurance policies mature 
their cash value and death benefits increase dramatically he gives 
as an example a healthy nonsmoking 38yearold male who buys 
250000 worth of whole life insurance for a premium of 3253 a 
year assuming the dividends continue to be paid as projected in 
10 years the policy will have a cash value slightly over the total 
premium paid plus a death benefit over the original 250000 
after 20 years the cash value and death benefit will be what 
goodstein terms significantly in excess of the premium 
investment 
to help realize this growth consumers should never buy a 
polity from a life insurance company that is rated less than aplus by 
am best amp co he says 
if the investor chooses a deferred annuity one that reinvests 
monthly dividends 100000 invested at the age of 45 can come to 
6000 a month 20 years later also assuming interest rates stay at 
or near current levels in comparing annuity interest rates 
consumers should consider both the historical performance as well 
as projected levels goodstein says 
