<TEXT>
if you own your own business its critical to map out a 
shareholders agreement to avoid confusion and potentially higher 
estate taxes when you die according to nahum gordon an attorney 
and estate planning specialist 
gordon a partner of moroze sherman gordon amp gordon a new 
yorkbased law firm says that without such an agreement in place 
surviving family members wont have a clear idea of how long they 
can draw your salary or how to cash in on the value of your shares 
other shareholders who may not be ready to buy out the shares 
but want to minimize the payout may not want your surviving 
spouse or children as partners in the business 
then theres uncertainty among employees creditors and banks 
who dont know what will happen next 
and in the absence of an agreement the internal revenue service 
can claim a high value and subsequent higher estate taxes on 
the shares some of the factors irs is likely to look at include 
the type and history of the business the economic outlook and the 
role of the specific industry involved the earning and 
dividendpaying capacities of your company an assessment of good 
will or other intangibles stock sales and the size of the block of 
stock to be valued and typical market prices of stocks of similar 
businesses whose shares are publicly traded 
gordon says there is no standard form of shareholders 
agreements but six major issues need to be considered when drawing 
one up 
whether your spouse or children will remain as shareholders 
or if shares owned by the estate can be purchased you need to 
judge if surviving family members can function effectively in the 
business and if other partners are amenable to your familys 
participation 
an established price or the method of arriving at one for 
your shares should you decide that your spouse and children will 
not remain as shareholders so that these shares can be bought in 
arms length transactions 
potential technical difficulties in tax estate and corporate 
laws resolve these in advance instead of leaving them to be dealt 
with under settlement pressure after your death 
additional benefits for your family if the proceeds of share 
sales wont meet their needs these can be in form of insurance 
deferred compensation plans or limited salary continuation plans 
adequate insurance to enable stock purchasers either family 
or the company to complete a buyout of the shares as spelled out 
in the agreement 
advance approval by banks or other thirdparty institutions 
whose consent will be needed to purchase or sell your shares after 
your death 
gordon says that the agreed purchase price usually will be 
conclusive except in some circumstances among closelyrelated 
parties 
</TEXT>
