<TEXT>
jane weston wilson is the author of the 
lifestyle cookbook eating well when you just cant eat the way 
you used to workman publishing 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as a child believing in magic i thought if i 
wrote down new years resolutions it was the same as doing them 
dont talk back to your grandmother brush your teeth practice 
the piano every day after school 
as adults the same belief in magic may hold true especially 
when it comes to resolutions involving health and fitness go on a 
strict diet get to a gym such promises often are made as we reach 
for a third chocolate mocha truffle or savor a second piece of aunt 
saras oyster loaf while watching the bowl games 
theres no doubt few of us get through the holidays without 
overdoing but there are other occasions for splurging birthdays 
bar mitzvahs anniversaries travel a favorite restaurant 
do we go on the teetertotter route of dieting then putting the 
weight back on or do we develop a new style of eating that 
maintains a healthy weight over a lifetime even when metabolism 
slows and it is easier to gain weight and harder to lose it a way 
of eating that allows for special times to splurge and makes every 
day the occasion for feasting lightly 
my solution is not to deprive ourselves of good food that never 
works it is simply to change portions and proportions 
choose twothirds of your food from the vegetable kingdom 
grains beans vegetables and fruits abounding in color variety 
vitamins and minerals and onethird from the animal kingdom 
meat fish fowl and dairy products with more calories from fat 
and cholesterol 
by becoming aware of this simple formula when we plan meals and 
shop the healthful balance is achieved without having to count 
calories a resolution that soon goes by the board 
following are three recipes that use this formula one you can 
easily adapt in your own cooking 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
pound cooked shrimp finely chopped or 
pound cooked chicken finely chopped 
1 cup finely chopped scallions 
1 cup peeled and shredded carrots 
1 cup finely chopped chinese or regular cabbage 
cup finely chopped cashews 
2 teaspoons corn oil 
1 teaspoon sesame oil 
1 teaspoon curry powder 
teaspoon ground cumin 
salt and freshly ground pepper to taste 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
1 in a medium bowl combine the shrimp or chicken with the 
scallions carrots cabbage and cashews 
2 in a large saucepan over medium heat heat the oils add 
seasonings and saute one minute stirring 
3 add the shrimp or chicken mixture and saute until heated 
through about five minutes 
4 transfer to a serving platter and serve hot leftovers can be 
served hot or cold 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
pound firm fish fillet such as scrod cod salmon halibut 
weakfish or sea bass washed and patted dry 
2 tablespoons freshly squeezed lime juice 
teaspoon dried leaf thyme 
1 teaspoon unsalted butter 
13 cup finely chopped yellow onion 
13 cup finely chopped green pepper 
13 cup finely chopped red pepper 
tomato coarsely chopped 
2 slices of lemon with rind coarsely chopped 
1 tablespoon coarsely chopped fresh basil or snipped dill for 
garnish 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
1 in a medium glass bowl place the fish lime juice and thyme 
marainate for a halfhour at room temperature or an hour in the 
refrigerator 
2 in a medium skillet over low heat melt one teaspoon butter 
add the chopped onions and peppers and saute until translucent 
about three to four minutes 
3 add the fish cover and cook for about seven minutes or until 
the fish flakes with a fork 
4 add the tomato and lemon and continue cooking for two to 
three minutes longer 
5 transfer to a serving platter and serve hot 
note this dish can also be prepared with chicken instead of 
fish and you can add other seasonal vegetables for color and 
variety 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
serves 2equals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
2 cups cooked fusili 
pound poached boneless chicken breasts cut into cubes 
