editors note george bria retired from the ap in 1981 after 40 
years that included coverage of world war ii from italy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
its catalog time for gardeners the 
season to sit back and enjoy this years parade of matchless 
wonders and breeding triumphs 
i once needed only one catalog to fuel my dreams now ive 
gotten choosy leafing through a halfdozen before i decide which 
tomatoes beans and lettuce will grace my garden come summer 
theres a catalog for everyone some quite artistically 
illustrated and you learn where to look for special things the 
tomato growers supply co of fort myers fla for example offers 
170 tomato varieties plus 41 peppers 
for a foreign touch numerous catalogs will bring europe or the 
orient to your backyard among them thompson amp morgan of 
jackson nj the cooks garden of londonderry vt and 
shepherds garden seeds of felton calif 
not to be outdone such a venerable seed house as w atlee 
burpee amp co of warminster pa now has an international 
vegetable section in its catalog 
a catalog buff can unlock the gate to just about anything in a 
wideranging volume by barbara j barton of san francisco 
gardening by mail published by tusker press it lists more 
than 1200 nurseries and seed companies and more than 300 garden 
supply and service companies in the united states and canada 
indexed by plant product and location 
for some of us nothing equals nurturing our own tomato plants 
from tiny seeds to fruitladen glory but were becoming a 
diminished breed more and more are foregoing the seed catalogs and 
opting for readytogo plants 
much gets sacrificed in this choice variety of course 
suffers but the joy of gardening itself seems diminished to a 
purist growing from purchased plants is like painting from 
numbers putting a roll in the pianola or wearing snapon bow ties 
pure snobbery you might say with more than a little 
justification the nurseryacquired plant still needs tender loving 
care fertilizing weeding watering 
experts familiar with gardening trends see many causes behind 
the phenomenon nona koivula executive director of the national 
garden bureau in willowbrook ill which promotes gardening from 
seed says timesaving is a prime reason for picking up a 
flourishing flat at the nursery instead of a seed packet in 
tomatoes you save three months of work by buying plants ready to 
set in the ground 
also home vegetable gardens have shrunk dramatically in size a 
gallup poll for the national gardening association of burlington 
vt showed the typical plot nowadays reduced to 200 square feet 
from 595 square feet 10 years ago trimmeddown gardens just dont 
have room for multiple varieties 
and the number of vegetable gardens also declined from 33 
million to 31 million in the 1980s people found there were more 
bullish investments than a vegetable plot in the backyard the 
associations magazine said 
whether the garden is small or large tomatoes remain the 
overwhelmingly favorite crop followed by peppers onions 
cucumbers beans lettuce carrots corn radishes and cabbages 
the poll showed curiously broccoli a powerhouse nutritionally 
and easy to grow doesnt rank at all in backyard popularity 
every year catalogs abound in new and improved varieties each 
introduced with a drumroll of amiable hype breeders appear to be 
concentrating on disease resistance with more and more maladies 
conquered by stalwart new entries 
people who think flavor is bred out this way can find seedhouses 
that specialize in heirloom varieties or scan seedswapping 
sections of gardening magazines on the chance of discovering an 
oldtime favorite offered for trade 
now and then studying the catalogs produces a winner a couple 
years ago i found a broccoli called romanesco which takes a 
long time to mature but climaxes in a glorious chartreuse head 
cauliflower texture and great taste 
you wont see it in the supermarket and its not likely to show 
up at the nursery youve got to raise it from seed but its not 
really new a bit of research showed its an heirloom italian 
variety just now appearing in us catalogs 
</TEXT>
