<TEXT>
ford motor co will give up on automatic seat 
belts by the mid1990s opting instead for air bags in all of its 
cars for drivers and frontseat passengers vice chairman harold 
poling says 
all of our tests have shown that when the passenger is 
properly positioned with the active belt plus the use of the air 
bag it provides the greatest protection in the event of an 
accident poling said sunday night at a news conference 
his comments came before he spoke to the opening session of an 
annual industry meeting sponsored by the trade weekly automotive 
news 
currently ford offers air bags on about half of its 2 million 
or so car fleet chrysler corp makes driverside air bags standard 
on all of its north americanmade cars and general motors corp 
has the devices as standard equipment on about 15 percent of its 
fleet 
by the 1993 model year federal regulations require automakers 
to have socalled passive restraint systems in place for drivers 
and frontseat passengers whether they are air bags with manual 
seat belts or automatic seat belts and no air bags 
the government required that cars made after sept 1 1989 be 
equipped with either a driverside air bag used in conjunction with 
manually operated seat belts for frontseat riders or automatic 
seat belts 
as the automakers were introducing their 1990 model cars they 
announced price increases of up to 5 percent over 1989 prices 
blaming most of the boosts on the safety devices 
direct comparisons of the cost of an air bag and an automatic 
seat belt system are difficult because of the wide variety of 
vehicle designs however air bags cost more to install and replace 
than do automatic seat belts 
poling said he didnt know how much it would cost to equip 
fords entire automobile fleet with driver and passengerside air 
bags by the mid1990s 
he estimated however it would add 400 to 600 to the cost of 
making each car about half of the cost of air bags now 
poling who on march 1 succeeds donald petersen as fords 
chairman also said that the company doesnt plan any major 
acquisitions in the near future during the second half of 1989 
ford spent nearly 6 billion to acquire the british luxury carmaker 
jaguar plc and the associates corp a financing company 
however poling said fords 25 percent stake in mazda the 
japanese automaker which which it jointly makes cars may grow 
if the opportunity occurred over time to increase our equity 
position with mazda poling said we would look at it 
favorably 
in his speech poling said the european auto market shows more 
potential for growth during the 1990s than does the north american 
market with projected increases of 15 percent and 1 percent 
respectively 
that combined with increased production capacity adds up to a 
rough decade for automakers 
the combination of excess capacity and slow growth in the 
automotive market will present a severe competitive challenge for 
car and truck manufacturers around the world he said 
however poling said automakers should have the chance to crack 
newly emerging markets including eastern europe and the soviet 
union 
