<TEXT>
financially troubled china and crystal maker 
waterford wedgwood group plc monday confirmed it is holding talks 
that might lead to a cash offer for a major but not controlling 
interest in the company 
waterford wedgwood shares gained 5 pence or 8 cents to 58 
pence on londons stock exchange on the news 
there has been widespread speculation for some time that 
waterford has been searching for a minority shareholder to give it 
a muchneeded cash infusion to help reduce some of the companys 
substantial debt 
the likely suitor is fitzwilton holdings plc a mediumsized 
cashrich irish industrial conglomerate said to be willing to take 
up to a 30percent holding in waterford wedgwood weekend press 
reports said 
a spokesman at fitzwilton who wasnt identified in accordance 
with british practice declined to comment 
however dublinbased sources speaking on condition of 
anonymity said that only fitzwiltons chairman tony oreilly and 
a group of highpowered investors have made an informal approach to 
the company oreilly also serves as chairman and chief executive 
of pittsburghbased hj heinz co 
regardless of who takes up the stake the sources said that 
about 120 million waterford wedgwood shares would be offered or 
30percent of the company at about 40 irish pence or 63 cents a 
share a deep discount from its current trading price of 62 irish 
pence in dublin 
waterford wedgwood has been suffering from serious financial 
problems in recent years an audit performed in late 1988 showed 
that accounting errors were made that significantly overvalued the 
companys inventories by up to 33 million waterford wedgwood 
chairman paddy hayes resigned after these revelations 
the company also has suffered from a decline in retail demand 
for its products in the united states and britain the appreciation 
of the irish pound against the dollar has hurt the companys 
fortunes 
last december the company warned that its would suffer a 
significant pretax loss in the second half 
