the first eastern european country to let its citizens use an 
international payment card 
the visa cards will be offered by zivnostenska banka the 
countrys oldest retail bank the bank initially intends to offer 
cards to customers with foreign currency incomes czechoslovakias 
currency isnt convertible into western currencies 
this not only marks a significant breakthrough to a new 
eastern european market it is a graphic illustration of the 
payment card as an international currency jeanjacques desbons 
executive vice president of visa international said in a statement 
czechoslovakia would follow the soviet union and china in 
accepting an international payment card 
the cards in czechoslovakia will be debit cards with purchase 
amounts billed immediately against the customers own accounts 
visa international spokesman david brancoli said czech customers 
will be able to use the card at any of the 75 million visa 
merchant locations worldwide he said 
since 1988 visa has issued a few thousand debit cards in the 
