<TEXT>
digital audio tape decks which offer the sound 
fidelity of compact discs along with the capability to record 
could be sold in the united states by the summer two leading 
japanese manufacturers say 
both matsushita electric industrial co which produces the 
panasonic and technics brands and sony corp say they hope to 
introduce the dat recorders in the us market sometime this year 
sony was vague on its plans but matsushita said at this weeks 
consumer electronics show that it will market a home recorder this 
summer at a price of about 1300 
the recorders longawaited by audio buffs have been on sale 
for several years overseas but their introduction to the us 
market had been held up by record companies who feared dats 
ability to make highquality tape recordings will encourage 
pirating and cut into their compact disc sales 
that issue was for the most part resolved last summer however 
when an agreement was reached on new technology that would allow 
direct copying onto a digital audio tape but would not allow 
unlimited copies to be made of those tapes 
manufacturers say they hope to capture a large segment of the 
highend audio market with the recorders despite their steep price 
tag in addition blank dat cassettes will cost 12 to 18 or more 
than twice the price of conventional blank cassettes the recording 
time of the dat tapes is similar to that of conventional cassettes 
i think it has the capability of being a very large market 
said john bermingham president of sonys us tape division 
compact discs and digital audio tape will exist together like lp 
albums and cassettes did before 
bermingham said sony envisions dat tapes which are about half 
the size of normal cassette tapes being used in its popular 
walkman stereos and in car stereos a consumer could record onto 
the tapes in his home tape deck and use them in the other 
applications he said 
you have some problems now with portable and car cds with 
taking them jogging or on a rough road bermingham said with 
dat you wouldnt have that problem 
both dats and cds use digital technology to reproduce music 
offering little distortion and high dynamic range in addition dat 
tapes lack the hiss that plagues conventional tape and many 
audiophiles believe it produces a deeper and more rich sound than 
compact discs 
but sales have been disappointing during the three years dat 
equipment has beem on the market in japan because of high prices 
and initial opposition from record industry groups 
under the july agreement which still must be codified by 
federal legislation new dat equipment will be able to make 
nearperfect direct digital recordings from digital sources such as 
cds but will add a flag signal to the tape to prevent any 
secondgeneration copies from being made from the tape 
while sony and matsushita were both displaying dat recorders at 
the electronics show general electric audio products announced at 
the show that it has developed what it calls the first compact disc 
player that allows recording and rerecording 
a spokesman for the company which is owned by thomson sa of 
france called the system the first major advancement in the 
format since cd technology was introduced but said it will not 
be available to consumers for at least a year 
the new system uses magneto optical discs for recording but is 
playback compatible with cds now on the market 
though ge claimed its recorder was the first sony said in 
october that it also had developed a magneto optical cd recorder 
thought it also was not yet ready for market 
</TEXT>
